      <!-- Introduction Section -->
      <section id="introduction" class="py-16 px-8">
        <div class="container mx-auto max-w-4xl">
          <h2 class="serif-heading text-4xl font-bold mb-8 text-center">Introduction to Super-capacitors</h2>

          <div id="definition" class="mb-16">
            <h3 class="serif-heading text-2xl font-semibold mb-6">Definition and Overview</h3>

            <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
              <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
                A supercapacitor (SC), also referred to as an ultracapacitor, is a high-capacity electrochemical energy storage device that bridges the performance gap between conventional electrolytic capacitors and rechargeable batteries <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supercapacitor" class="citation" target="_blank">15</a>. Unlike standard capacitors that utilize a solid dielectric material, supercapacitors employ <strong>electrostatic double-layer capacitance and electrochemical pseudocapacitance</strong> to store energy <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supercapacitor" class="citation" target="_blank">15</a>.
              </p>

              <div class="highlight-box">
                <h4 class="font-semibold mb-3">Key Characteristics</h4>
                <ul class="space-y-2">
                  <li><strong>High Capacitance:</strong> Stores 10 to 100 times more energy per unit mass or volume than conventional capacitors</li>
                  <li><strong>Rapid Charge/Discharge:</strong> Accepts and delivers charge much faster than batteries</li>
                  <li><strong>Long Cycle Life:</strong> Endures hundreds of thousands to millions of cycles with minimal degradation</li>
                  <li><strong>High Power Density:</strong> Ideal for applications requiring rapid bursts of power</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
                The fundamental architecture of a supercapacitor consists of two electrodes, an electrolyte, and a separator that prevents direct electrical contact between the electrodes. The choice of electrode materials and electrolytes plays a crucial role in determining the device&#39;s overall performance, including its energy density, power density, and operational voltage window <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supercapacitor" class="citation" target="_blank">15</a>.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div id="history" class="mb-16">
            <h3 class="serif-heading text-2xl font-semibold mb-6">Historical Development and Key Milestones</h3>

            <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
              <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
                The history of supercapacitors dates back to the early 1950s when engineers at General Electric began experimenting with porous carbon electrodes in the design of capacitors, drawing inspiration from fuel cell and rechargeable battery technologies <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supercapacitor" class="citation" target="_blank">15</a>.
              </p>

              <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 my-8">
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                  <div class="flex items-center mb-4">
                    <div class="w-3 h-3 bg-blue-500 rounded-full mr-3"></div>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-700">1957 - The Beginning</span>
                  </div>
                  <p class="text-gray-600">H. Becker developed a &#34;Low voltage electrolytic capacitor with porous carbon electrodes&#34; at General Electric, noting extremely high capacity but not fully understanding the underlying mechanism <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supercapacitor" class="citation" target="_blank">15</a>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                  <div class="flex items-center mb-4">
                    <div class="w-3 h-3 bg-green-500 rounded-full mr-3"></div>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-700">1966 - SOHIO Innovation</span>
                  </div>
                  <p class="text-gray-600">Researchers at Standard Oil of Ohio developed another version as an &#34;electrical energy storage apparatus&#34; while working on experimental fuel cell designs <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supercapacitor" class="citation" target="_blank">15</a>.</p>
                </div>
              </div>

              <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
                The 1990s saw a surge in research activity, with the number of non-patent publications on supercapacitors increasing tenfold every seven years <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supercapacitor" class="citation" target="_blank">15</a>. This period was marked by the development of new electrode materials, including metal oxides and conductive polymers, which introduced pseudocapacitance as a complementary energy storage mechanism.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div id="landscape" class="mb-16">
            <h3 class="serif-heading text-2xl font-semibold mb-6">Role in the Modern Energy Landscape</h3>

            <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
              <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
                In the modern energy landscape, supercapacitors have emerged as a critical technology for addressing the growing demand for efficient, reliable, and sustainable energy storage solutions. Their unique combination of <strong>high power density, fast charge-discharge capabilities, and long cycle life</strong> makes them an ideal choice for a wide range of applications, from portable electronics to grid-scale energy storage <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2313-0105/11/6/232" class="citation" target="_blank">2</a>.
              </p>

              <div class="image-container my-8">
                <img src="https://kimi-web-img.moonshot.cn/img/www.led-professional.com/6e6dd76b505bb2794c0ab4e0a54ed76a256393e5.png" alt="Supercapacitors integrated with solar panels and wind turbines" class="w-full" size="large" aspect="wide" style="photo" query="renewable energy supercapacitor integration" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" data-modified="1" data-score="0.00"/>
                <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-t from-black/30 to-transparent"></div>
                <div class="absolute bottom-4 left-4 text-white">
                  <p class="text-sm">Supercapacitors in renewable energy systems</p>
                </div>
              </div>

              <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
                The transportation sector is another key area where supercapacitors are making a significant impact. In electric and hybrid electric vehicles, supercapacitors are used for <strong>regenerative braking</strong>, capturing and storing energy that would otherwise be lost during deceleration <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supercapacitor" class="citation" target="_blank">15</a>. The <strong>Lamborghini Sian FKP 37</strong>, for instance, integrates a supercapacitor to boost acceleration alongside its V12 engine, showcasing the potential of this technology in high-performance automotive applications <a href="https://www.evengineeringonline.com/hypocap-an-award-winning-breakthrough-in-supercapacitor-energy/" class="citation" target="_blank">222</a>.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
