      <section id="principles" class="py-16 px-8 bg-gray-50">
        <div class="container mx-auto max-w-4xl">
          <h2 class="serif-heading text-4xl font-bold mb-8 text-center">Fundamental Principles and Classification</h2>

          <div id="mechanisms" class="mb-16">
            <h3 class="serif-heading text-2xl font-semibold mb-6">Energy Storage Mechanisms</h3>

            <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
              <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-8">
                Supercapacitors represent a distinct class of energy storage devices that bridge the gap between conventional capacitors and batteries. Their ability to store and deliver energy is rooted in electrochemical principles, which differ fundamentally from the purely electrostatic mechanisms of traditional capacitors <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2313-0105/11/6/232" class="citation" target="_blank">2</a>.
              </p>

              <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 mb-8">
                <div class="bg-white p-8 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                  <h4 class="serif-heading text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-blue-600">
                    <i class="fas fa-layer-group mr-3"></i>Electrostatic Double-Layer Capacitance (EDLC)
                  </h4>
                  <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
                    EDLCs operate on the principle of <strong>electrostatic charge separation</strong>, using high-surface-area porous materials like activated carbon to achieve significantly enhanced capacitance values <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2313-0105/11/6/232" class="citation" target="_blank">2</a>.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-blue-50 p-4 rounded-lg">
                    <p class="text-sm text-blue-800">
                      <strong>Key Features:</strong> Purely physical charge storage, exceptionally high power density, rapid charge/discharge, extremely long cycle life.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-white p-8 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                  <h4 class="serif-heading text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-green-600">
                    <i class="fas fa-atom mr-3"></i>Electrochemical Pseudocapacitance
                  </h4>
                  <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
                    Pseudocapacitors store energy through <strong>Faradaic reactions</strong> involving reversible redox reactions at the electrode surface, enabling significantly higher specific capacitance and energy densities <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2313-0105/11/6/232" class="citation" target="_blank">2</a>.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-green-50 p-4 rounded-lg">
                    <p class="text-sm text-green-800">
                      <strong>Key Features:</strong> Faradaic charge transfer, higher energy density, redox-active materials, fast surface kinetics.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="highlight-box">
                <h4 class="font-semibold mb-3">Hybrid Energy Storage Mechanisms</h4>
                <p class="mb-4">
                  Hybrid supercapacitors integrate both EDLC and pseudocapacitive mechanisms into a single device, typically through an asymmetric design that pairs a carbon-based electrode with a pseudocapacitive electrode <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2313-0105/11/6/232" class="citation" target="_blank">2</a>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  This approach synergistically combines the <strong>high power density and excellent cyclic stability of EDLCs with the high energy density characteristic of pseudocapacitors</strong>, creating next-generation energy storage systems that can meet demanding requirements.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div id="classification" class="mb-16">
            <h3 class="serif-heading text-2xl font-semibold mb-6">Classification of Super-capacitors</h3>

            <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
              <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-8">
                Supercapacitors are broadly classified into three primary categories based on their underlying energy storage mechanisms and the materials used in their construction: <strong>electrochemical double-layer capacitors (EDLCs), pseudocapacitors, and hybrid capacitors</strong>
                <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2313-0105/11/6/232" class="citation" target="_blank">2</a>.
              </p>

              <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 mb-8">
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md text-center">
                  <div class="w-16 h-16 bg-blue-100 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-4">
                    <i class="fas fa-layer-group text-2xl text-blue-600"></i>
                  </div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">EDLCs</h4>
                  <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Carbon-based materials, electrostatic storage, high power density</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md text-center">
                  <div class="w-16 h-16 bg-green-100 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-4">
                    <i class="fas fa-atom text-2xl text-green-600"></i>
                  </div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Pseudocapacitors</h4>
                  <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Metal oxides/conductive polymers, Faradaic reactions, high energy density</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md text-center">
                  <div class="w-16 h-16 bg-purple-100 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-4">
                    <i class="fas fa-puzzle-piece text-2xl text-purple-600"></i>
                  </div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Hybrid</h4>
                  <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Combined mechanisms, asymmetric design, balanced performance</p>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white p-8 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <h4 class="serif-heading text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Electrolyte-Based Classification</h4>
                <p class="mb-4">
                  Supercapacitors can also be classified based on their electrolyte type, which significantly impacts performance characteristics <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-025-24042-3" class="citation" target="_blank">228</a>:
                </p>
                <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
                  <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-4">
                    <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-700">Aqueous Electrolytes</h5>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">High conductivity, low cost, narrow voltage window (1.2V)</p>
                  </div>
                  <div class="border-l-4 border-green-500 pl-4">
                    <h5 class="font-semibold text-green-700">Organic Electrolytes</h5>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Wider voltage window (2.7V), commercial standard</p>
                  </div>
                  <div class="border-l-4 border-purple-500 pl-4">
                    <h5 class="font-semibold text-purple-700">Ionic Liquids</h5>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Very wide window (3.5-4.0V), high thermal stability</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <div class="section-divider"></div>

      <!-- Electrode Materials Section -->
      <section id="electrodes" class="py-16 px-8">
        <div class="container mx-auto max-w-4xl">
          <h2 class="serif-heading text-4xl font-bold mb-8 text-center">Core Components: Electrode Materials</h2>

          <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none mb-12">
            <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
              The performance of a supercapacitor is fundamentally dictated by the properties of its constituent materials, with the electrode material playing the most critical role. An ideal electrode material must possess a unique combination of characteristics to ensure optimal device performance <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2313-0105/11/6/232" class="citation" target="_blank">2</a>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div id="carbon" class="mb-16">
            <h3 class="serif-heading text-2xl font-semibold mb-6">Carbon-Based Materials</h3>

            <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
              <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Carbon-based materials have long been the cornerstone of supercapacitor electrode technology, particularly for EDLCs, due to their exceptional combination of properties. These materials are characterized by their <strong>high specific surface area (SSA)</strong>, excellent electrical conductivity, and remarkable chemical and thermal stability <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2313-0105/11/6/232" class="citation" target="_blank">2</a>.
              </p>

              <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 mb-8">
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                  <h4 class="serif-heading text-lg font-semibold mb-4 text-blue-600">
                    <i class="fas fa-fire mr-2"></i>Activated Carbon (AC)
                  </h4>
                  <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
                    The most widely used commercial electrode material, with specific surface areas exceeding <strong>2000 m²/g</strong>. Created through carbonization and activation of carbon-rich precursors like coconut shells and wood <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2313-0105/11/6/232" class="citation" target="_blank">2</a>.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-blue-50 p-3 rounded">
                    <p class="text-sm text-blue-800">
                      <strong>Structure:</strong> Network of micropores (
                      &lt; 2 nm) and mesopores (2-50 nm) for ion adsorption and transport</p>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                  <h4 class="serif-heading text-lg font-semibold mb-4 text-green-600">
                    <i class="fas fa-hexagon mr-2"></i>Graphene and rGO
                  </h4>
                  <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
                    Single-layer sp²-hybridized carbon atoms with exceptional theoretical specific surface area of <strong>2630 m²/g</strong> and outstanding electrical conductivity <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2313-0105/11/6/232" class="citation" target="_blank">2</a>.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-green-50 p-3 rounded">
                    <p class="text-sm text-green-800">
                      <strong>Challenge:</strong> Preventing restacking and aggregation of graphene sheets
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="highlight-box">
                <h4 class="font-semibold mb-3">Carbon Nanotubes and Carbon Nanofibers</h4>
                <p class="mb-4">
                  One-dimensional carbon materials with high aspect ratio, excellent electrical conductivity, and unique porous structure that facilitates rapid ion transport. CNTs can be single-walled (SWCNTs) or multi-walled (MWCNTs), creating highly conductive pathways throughout the electrode <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2313-0105/11/6/232" class="citation" target="_blank">2</a>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Performance Example:</strong> SWCNTs as spacers in graphene-based supercapacitors achieved <strong>261 F/g specific capacitance and 123 Wh/kg energy density</strong> at 3.7V operating voltage.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div id="metal-oxides" class="mb-16">
            <h3 class="serif-heading text-2xl font-semibold mb-6">Transition Metal Oxides and Sulfides</h3>

            <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
              <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Transition metal oxides (TMOs) and sulfides (TMSs) have emerged as highly promising electrode materials for pseudocapacitors, offering significantly higher energy densities compared to carbon-based EDLCs. These materials store charge through <strong>fast and reversible Faradaic redox reactions</strong> at their surface <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2313-0105/11/6/232" class="citation" target="_blank">2</a>.
              </p>

              <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg border-l-4 border-blue-500">
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-700 mb-3">Ruthenium Oxide (RuO₂)</h4>
                  <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
                    Considered the gold standard with <strong>specific capacitance exceeding 1000 F/g</strong>, excellent electrical conductivity, and outstanding electrochemical stability <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2313-0105/11/6/232" class="citation" target="_blank">2</a>.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-red-50 p-3 rounded">
                    <p class="text-sm text-red-800">
                      <strong>Limitation:</strong> High cost and toxicity of ruthenium limit commercial applications
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg border-l-4 border-green-500">
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-700 mb-3">Manganese Dioxide (MnO₂)</h4>
                  <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
                    Abundant, inexpensive, and environmentally benign alternative with <strong>theoretical specific capacitance up to 1370 F/g</strong>
                    <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2313-0105/11/6/232" class="citation" target="_blank">2</a>.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-yellow-50 p-3 rounded">
                    <p class="text-sm text-yellow-800">
                      <strong>Challenge:</strong> Poor electrical conductivity limits rate capability
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg border-l-4 border-purple-500">
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-purple-700 mb-3">Nickel Oxide (NiO)</h4>
                  <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
                    High theoretical specific capacitance of <strong>approximately 2584 F g⁻¹</strong>, with charge storage based on reversible redox reaction between Ni²⁺ and Ni³⁺/Ni⁴⁺ states <a href="https://advanced.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/aesr.202400412" class="citation" target="_blank">41</a>.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-blue-50 p-3 rounded">
                    <p class="text-sm text-blue-800">
                      <strong>Performance:</strong> Al-doped Ni(OH)₂ nanosheets demonstrated <strong>2123 F g⁻¹</strong> specific capacitance
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg border-l-4 border-orange-500">
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-orange-700 mb-3">Cobalt Oxide (Co₃O₄)</h4>
                  <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
                    Very high theoretical specific capacitance of <strong>up to 3560 F g⁻¹</strong>, with rich redox chemistry involving Co²⁺/Co³⁺ and Co³⁺/Co⁴⁺ couples <a href="https://advanced.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/aesr.202400412" class="citation" target="_blank">41</a>.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-green-50 p-3 rounded">
                    <p class="text-sm text-green-800">
                      <strong>Achievement:</strong> 3D hollow structures reached <strong>820 F g⁻¹</strong> specific capacitance
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-purple-50 to-pink-50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-purple-200">
                <h4 class="font-semibold text-purple-700 mb-3">
                  <i class="fas fa-star mr-2"></i>Transition Metal Sulfides - Emerging Stars
                </h4>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
                  Transition metal sulfides (TMSs) offer superior performance compared to their oxide counterparts. The substitution of oxygen with sulfur leads to materials with <strong>higher electrical conductivity and more flexible structures</strong>, resulting in enhanced rate capability and improved cycling stability <a href="https://pubs.rsc.org/en/content/articlelanding/2025/ra/d5ra02905h" class="citation" target="_blank">33</a>.
                </p>
                <div class="bg-white p-4 rounded border">
                  <p class="text-sm text-gray-800">
                    <strong>Outstanding Performance:</strong> NiMoO₄@NiCo₂S₄ composite achieved <strong>2565.2 F g⁻¹</strong> specific capacitance, delivering <strong>75.3 Wh kg⁻¹</strong> energy density at <strong>800 W kg⁻¹</strong> power density <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12451529/" class="citation" target="_blank">59</a>.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div id="polymers" class="mb-16">
            <h3 class="serif-heading text-2xl font-semibold mb-6">Conductive Polymers</h3>

            <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
              <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Conductive polymers (CPs) represent another vital class of pseudocapacitive materials, offering a unique combination of properties that make them highly attractive for supercapacitor electrodes. Unlike rigid inorganic materials, CPs are <strong>flexible, lightweight, and can be synthesized through relatively simple and low-cost chemical or electrochemical polymerization methods</strong>
                <a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S2352152X24002822" class="citation" target="_blank">54</a>.
              </p>

              <div class="mermaid-container">
                <div class="mermaid-controls">
                  <button class="mermaid-control-btn zoom-in" title="放大">
                    <i class="fas fa-search-plus"></i>
                  </button>
                  <button class="mermaid-control-btn zoom-out" title="缩小">
                    <i class="fas fa-search-minus"></i>
                  </button>
                  <button class="mermaid-control-btn reset-zoom" title="重置">
                    <i class="fas fa-expand-arrows-alt"></i>
                  </button>
                  <button class="mermaid-control-btn fullscreen" title="全屏查看">
                    <i class="fas fa-expand"></i>
